ble-content"><div dir=3D"auto" class=3D"body markup"><p></p><p><span>Rob He=
nderson=E2=80=99s Office Hours are here. I=E2=80=99ll be doing these livest=
reams every Wednesday at 8 PM ET=E2=80=94except next week, we=E2=80=99re sh=
ifting to Tuesday at 2pm ET when I=E2=80=99ll be doing a livestream with be=
stselling author and Substacker </span><a href=3D"https://www.twopct.com/" =
rel=3D"">Michael Easter</a><span>.</span></p><p>Some topics covered in this=
 first installment:</p><ul><li><p>Social media is turning us into informant=
s. The rise of public shaming, the digital panopticon, and why people fear =
speaking openly. Communist regimes needed secret police; we just needed pho=
nes and the promise of =E2=80=9Clikes.=E2=80=9D</p></li><li><p><span>Christ=
opher Lasch saw this coming in 1979 =E2=80=93 Revisiting </span><em>The Cul=
ture of Narcissism</em><span> and how it explains today=E2=80=99s world bet=
ter than ever.</span></p></li><li><p>Why people work harder to avoid critic=
ism than to improve their lives =E2=80=93 A counterintuitive but useful way=
 to understand human behavior.</p></li><li><p>The hidden shift in how peopl=
e talk about themselves online =E2=80=93 How =E2=80=9CI had someone tell me=
=E2=80=A6=E2=80=9D reflects the rise of main character syndrome.</p></li><l=
i><p>Do young people actually want attention? =E2=80=93 Why social media cu=
lture has made them both more risk-averse and more eager to be influencers.=
</p></li><li><p>Everything online is curated=E2=80=94even when it looks rea=
l =E2=80=93 The difference between reality and the highly manicured world o=
f digital life.</p></li><li><p>The truth about online trolls. Research show=
s that the worst people on social media aren=E2=80=99t just nasty online=E2=
=80=94they=E2=80=99re like that in real life, too.</p></li><li><p>Why socia=
l media feels worse than it actually is. A small percentage of users create=
 most of the content, and negativity spreads the fastest=E2=80=94so we thin=
k society is crueler than it really is.</p></li><li><p>The new acceptable t=
argets for public ridicule. You can=E2=80=99t mock some groups anymore, so =
people are finding new ones they can still go after.</p></li><li><p>How com=
panies are tracking you (even when you think they aren=E2=80=99t). I share =
a quick story about how Best Buy tried to get my personal data just because=
